4MB87mJ4VbfjixjXo4Q4S20ETuKFphL_whXFdMlBg-Bjr-9K9di5OJAM51HsWt_3pNI30Wbyx6uzvOEg035vnOj_lWXhZBT2D1y4ImPdaUJQgXTXD2QjKa2OS6e68TrvQic3E_80PQR8CRrghL1r9PhMFTIyZvl7R_ZfqcOJSKFLSsuqnt73S75CkbJK1G-gCxaArn1e8yerqvowlAogQLQHVdTpJ6WrIEwnIT7-hqAo9YB81NKadRzWO17tbZh0QzfLboD-xlvFq0qrAPsPapdhUJ5Zt6HYpAYQiVnDP4n8WMBbjHyJ0oCGPJPBGCmscJP7-ryyRo75Pn4sdsUH65WfhO9dqDMRJqty0lDss-CBu-PB9lroUnNhRXBtWkAvzNV_Tfil5RnC7Wd7PybibYSH5tu98CxpXx6BKIhSW7TKJSpcjQ8dNSwZRRTiX40FIHopdo\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating actor style dependencies**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether I need an extra dependency for typed actor style. The target library is `pekko-actor_2.13`, which is core classic. Existing tests have removed `TypedActor`, so I need to prepare before moving forward. I wonder if adding `pekko-actor-typed_2.13:2.0.0-M1` is necessary for the modern API. The Apache Pekko docs recommend using typed actors, but they're separate from the classic actor module. It seems I can achieve meaningful coverage with just the core. Using `pekko-testkit` might help for testing, but I can reach coverage without it.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Java JUnit dependencies**\\n\\nI'm contemplating whether I need to generate a scaffold that typically relies on Java JUnit, or if I should consider that dependencies might not apply to the Scala compiler. It feels like there should be some clarity here regarding how Java dependencies mesh with Scala, especially if I’m not using JUnit in a standard way. I wonder if there's a nuanced approach I should take when integrating these frameworks. I'll need to dig into the specifics to ensure I'm not missing something important!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Researching dependencies**\\n\\nI’m thinking I might need to research the dependencies and documentation for version 2.0.0-M1. It seems like checking the Javadocs could be helpful, but I'm not sure if everything is there. I should also consider the modules and perhaps see if they have any details about typedactors since I’m uncertain about that. Additionally, using cURL documentation might provide some insights. There's a lot to investigate, but I’m looking forward to digging in!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_vTrrDPI2yEPbNOhTi8ZFc84G|fc_0877bea9f7e2dd08016a4275fc57b88197943702eed7902e94", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request, re\nurls=[\n 'https://pekko.apache.org/docs/pekko/2.0.0-M1/typed/index.html',\n 'https://pekko.apache.org/docs/pekko/2.0.0-M1/project/migration-guides.html',\n 'https://pekko.apache.org/docs/pekko/2.0.0-M1/project/migration-guides/migration-guide-2.0.x.html',\n 'https://pekko.apache.org/docs/pekko/2.0.0-M1/index.html',\n]\nfor url in urls:\n print('\\nURL',url)\n try:\n  txt=urllib.request.urlopen(url, timeout=20).read().decode('utf-8','ignore')\n  print('len',len(txt),'title', re.search(r'<title>(.*?)</title>', txt, re.S).group(1) if re.search(r'<title>(.*?)</title>', txt, re.S) else '')\n  for pat in ['typed', 'dependency', 'pekko-actor-typed', 'pekko-actor_2.13', 'testkit', 'Docker', 'system property']:\n   i=txt.lower().find(pat.lower())\n   if i>=0: print(pat, re.sub('<[^>]+>',' ',txt[max(0,i-200):i+500])[:500].replace('\\n',' '))\n except Exception as e: print('ERR', e)\nPY", "timeout": 60}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 840, "output": 909, "cacheRead": 24064, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 25813, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782740463164, "responseId": "resp_0877bea9f7e2dd08016a4275ef94bc8197aa7b289fc5b8c00e"}}
